  "prompt": "Which leaf is necessary for green tea? What are different types of green tea?",
  "response": "For green tea, the leaf from the Camellia sinensis plant is used, specifically the young, tender leaves and buds. Here are some different types of green tea:\n\n1. Japanese Green Tea Types:\n- Sencha (most common)\n- Gyokuro (shade-grown, high-quality tea)\n- Matcha (powdered green tea)\n- Genmaicha (green tea with roasted rice)\n- Hojicha (roasted green tea)\n- Bancha (coarse, late-harvest tea)\n\n2. Chinese Green Tea Types:\n- Longjing (Dragon Well)\n- Bi Luo Chun\n- Gunpowder Green Tea\n- Huangshan Maofeng\n- Liu An Gua Pian\n- Taiping Houkui\n\n3. Other Green Tea Varieties:\n- Korean Green Tea\n- Vietnamese Green Tea\n- Turkish Green Tea\n\nEach type of green tea has unique processing methods, flavor profiles, and cultural significance. The primary difference lies in cultivation techniques, harvesting time, and processing methods like steaming (Japanese style) or pan-firing (Chinese style).\n\nThe Camellia sinensis plant is the source for all true teas: green, black, white, oolong, and pu-erh tea.",
